04607nam a22005535i 9780822394952DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20122012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780822394952  a(DE-B1597)552389  a(OCoLC)1167393553  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHV875.55b.B75 2012eb 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a362.73409731 aBriggs, Laura, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSomebody's Children :bThe Politics of Transracial and Transnational Adoption /cLaura Briggs. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (376 p.) :b7 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPART I. Transracial Adoption in the United States -- tOne. African American Children and Adoption, 1950–1975 -- tTwo. The Making of the Indian Child Welfare Act, 1922–1978 -- tThree. ‘‘Crack Babies,’’ Race, and Adoption Reform, 1975–2000 -- tPART II. Transnational Adoption and Latin America -- tFour. From Refugees to Madonnas of the Cold War -- tFive. Uncivil Wars -- tSix. Latin American Family Values -- tPART III. Emerging Fights over the Politics of Adoption -- tSeven. Gay and Lesbian Adoption in the United States -- tEpilogue U.S. Immigrants: The Next Fight over Race, Adoption, and Foster Care? -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Somebody's Children, Laura Briggs examines the social and cultural forces—poverty, racism, economic inequality, and political violence—that have shaped transracial and transnational adoption in the United States during the second half of the twentieth century and the first decade of the twenty-first. Focusing particularly on the experiences of those who have lost their children to adoption, Briggs analyzes the circumstances under which African American and Native mothers in the United States and indigenous and poor women in Latin America have felt pressed to give up their children for adoption or have lost them involuntarily.The dramatic expansion of transracial and transnational adoption since the 1950s, Briggs argues, was the result of specific and profound political and social changes, including the large-scale removal of Native children from their parents, the condemnation of single African American mothers in the context of the civil rights struggle, and the largely invented "crack babies" scare that inaugurated the dramatic withdrawal of benefits to poor mothers in the United States. In Guatemala, El Salvador, and Argentina, governments disappeared children during the Cold War and then imposed neoliberal economic regimes with U.S. support, making the circulation of children across national borders easy and often profitable. Concluding with an assessment of present-day controversies surrounding gay and lesbian adoptions and the struggles of immigrants fearful of losing their children to foster care, Briggs challenges celebratory or otherwise simplistic accounts of transracial and transnational adoption by revealing some of their unacknowledged causes and costs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAdoptionzUnited States. 0aChild welfarezUnited States. 0aIntercountry adoptionzUnited States. 0aInterracial adoptionzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107118370 cprintz978082235147440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822394952423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822394952/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aE